SOLUTION:
Step 1: Create the Project Structure
First, you need to understand the folder structure. In Terraform, modules are simply folders containing .tf files:

ex2_terraform_modules/
├── main.tf              # Root configuration - where you call modules
├── variables.tf         # Root variables - inputs for the whole project
├── outputs.tf           # Root outputs - what you want to see after deployment
├── configs/             # Environment-specific variable values
│   ├── dev.tfvars       # Development environment settings
│   └── prod.tfvars      # Production environment settings
└── modules/             # Your local reusable modules
    └── storage_account/ # One module = one folder
        ├── main.tf      # Module's resources
        ├── variables.tf # Module's inputs (parameters)
        └── outputs.tf   # Module's outputs (return values)
Key insight: The modules/storage_account/ folder has the same file structure as the root folder (main.tf, variables.tf, outputs.tf). That's because a module is just a mini-Terraform project that you can call from another project.

Create the directories:

mkdir -p ex2_terraform_modules/modules/storage_account
mkdir -p ex2_terraform_modules/configs
cd ex2_terraform_modules
Step 2: Create the Local Storage Account Module
Now you will create your first local module. This module will be a reusable "recipe" for creating Azure Storage Accounts. You will call this module twice - once for logging and once for data storage.

Why create a module for this?

Storage accounts require the same configuration every time (name, location, tier, replication). Instead of writing this code twice (or ten times), you write it once in a module and call it with different parameters.

File 1: modules/storage_account/variables.tf
This file defines the inputs (parameters) that your module accepts. Think of these as the "holes" that need to be filled when someone uses your module.

# The name of the storage account
# Azure requires storage account names to be globally unique across all Azure
variable "account_name" {
  description = "Name of the storage account (must be globally unique)"
  type        = string
}

# Where to create the storage account (e.g., "germanywestcentral")
variable "location" {
  description = "Azure region for the storage account"
  type        = string
}

# The resource group that will contain this storage account
variable "resource_group_name" {
  description = "Name of the resource group"
  type        = string
}

# Performance tier - Standard uses HDDs (cheaper), Premium uses SSDs (faster)
# Default is "Standard" - if caller doesn't specify, this value is used
variable "account_tier" {
  description = "Performance tier: Standard or Premium"
  type        = string
  default     = "Standard"
}
Notice: Every variable has a description - this is documentation for anyone using your module. The account_tier variable has a default value, making it optional when calling the module.

File 2: modules/storage_account/main.tf
This file contains the actual resource that the module creates. It uses the variables defined above.

# Create an Azure Storage Account
# This is the only resource in this module
resource "azurerm_storage_account" "storage" {
  # Use the values passed in through variables
  name                     = var.account_name
  resource_group_name      = var.resource_group_name
  location                 = var.location
  account_tier             = var.account_tier

  # LRS = Locally Redundant Storage (3 copies in same datacenter)
  # This is the cheapest option - good for dev/test environments
  account_replication_type = "LRS"

  # Tags help you organize and identify resources in Azure Portal
  tags = {
    Environment = "Terraform Modules Exercise"
  }
}
Key point: Notice how we use var.account_name instead of hardcoding a name. This is what makes the module reusable - each time you call it, you can pass a different name.

File 3: modules/storage_account/outputs.tf
This file defines what values the module returns after creating the resource. Think of these as the "results" that the caller can use.

# Return the blob storage endpoint URL
# Example: "https://mystorageaccount.blob.core.windows.net/"
# The caller might need this URL to configure other resources
output "primary_blob_endpoint" {
  description = "The primary blob endpoint URL"
  value       = azurerm_storage_account.storage.primary_blob_endpoint
}

# Return the full Azure resource ID
# Example: "/subscriptions/.../storageAccounts/mystorageaccount"
# Useful for referencing this storage account from other resources
output "storage_account_id" {
  description = "The ID of the storage account"
  value       = azurerm_storage_account.storage.id
}
Why outputs matter: After you call a module, you might need to know something about the created resource (like its URL or ID). Outputs let you "export" this information back to the caller.

Step 3: Create the Root Configuration
Now you will create the root configuration - this is the "main" Terraform project that calls your modules. Think of it as the "orchestrator" that brings everything together.

File 1: variables.tf (root)
These are the inputs for your entire project. Some will be passed to the modules.

# Azure region where all resources will be created
# Default is Germany West Central - change if needed
variable "location" {
  description = "Azure region for resources"
  type        = string
  default     = "germanywestcentral"
}

# Performance tier for storage accounts
# This value will be passed to both storage modules
variable "account_tier" {
  description = "Storage account tier: Standard or Premium"
  type        = string
  default     = "Standard"
}

# Name for the first storage account (logging)
# No default - must be provided when running terraform apply
variable "logging_storage_name" {
  description = "Name for the logging storage account"
  type        = string
}

# Name for the second storage account (data)
# No default - must be provided when running terraform apply
variable "data_storage_name" {
  description = "Name for the data storage account"
  type        = string
}
Key insight: Variables without defaults (logging_storage_name, data_storage_name) MUST be provided. You will provide them via .tfvars files.

File 2: main.tf (root)
This is the heart of your configuration. It creates resources directly AND calls modules.

# ============================================================
# TERRAFORM CONFIGURATION BLOCK
# Specifies which providers and versions this project needs
# ============================================================
terraform {
  required_providers {
    azurerm = {
      source  = "hashicorp/azurerm"  # Download from HashiCorp's registry
      version = "~> 4.0"              # Use version 4.x (but not 5.x)
    }
  }
  required_version = ">= 1.9.0"       # Minimum Terraform CLI version
}

# ============================================================
# PROVIDER CONFIGURATION
# Configures how Terraform connects to Azure
# ============================================================
provider "azurerm" {
  features {}  # Required block, even if empty
  # Authentication happens via Azure CLI (az login) - no credentials here
}

# ============================================================
# RESOURCE GROUP
# A container for all Azure resources in this project
# ============================================================
resource "azurerm_resource_group" "rg" {
  name     = "ModulesExerciseRG"
  location = var.location
}

# ============================================================
# REGISTRY MODULE: VIRTUAL NETWORK
# Using a pre-built module from Terraform Registry instead of
# writing all the VNet configuration ourselves
# ============================================================
# Azure Verified Modules (AVM) are official modules maintained by Microsoft
# Find them at: https://registry.terraform.io/namespaces/Azure
module "vnet" {
  # source = "NAMESPACE/MODULE_NAME/PROVIDER"
  source  = "Azure/avm-res-network-virtualnetwork/azurerm"
  version = "0.17.0"  # Always pin the version for reproducibility

  # Module inputs - check the module's documentation for available options
  name          = "ModuleVNet"
  location      = azurerm_resource_group.rg.location  # Reference the RG we created
  parent_id     = azurerm_resource_group.rg.id        # The RG's resource ID
  address_space = ["10.0.0.0/16"]                     # IP range for the VNet

  # Subnets are defined as a map of objects
  subnets = {
    "default" = {
      name             = "default"
      address_prefixes = ["10.0.1.0/24"]  # Subnet IP range (subset of VNet)
    }
  }

  tags = {
    Environment = "Terraform Modules Exercise"
  }
}

# ============================================================
# LOCAL MODULE CALL #1: LOGGING STORAGE
# Using our custom module to create the first storage account
# ============================================================
module "logging_storage" {
  # source = relative path to the module folder
  source = "./modules/storage_account"

  # Pass values to the module's variables
  account_name        = var.logging_storage_name      # From root variable
  location            = var.location                   # From root variable
  resource_group_name = azurerm_resource_group.rg.name # From resource we created
  account_tier        = var.account_tier               # From root variable
}

# ============================================================
# LOCAL MODULE CALL #2: DATA STORAGE
# Same module, different parameters = different storage account
# ============================================================
module "data_storage" {
  source = "./modules/storage_account"

  # Different name, but same location, RG, and tier
  account_name        = var.data_storage_name
  location            = var.location
  resource_group_name = azurerm_resource_group.rg.name
  account_tier        = var.account_tier
}
The "Factory" pattern: Notice how we call ./modules/storage_account twice with different account_name values. Each call creates a separate, independent storage account. This is the power of modules - write once, use many times.

File 3: outputs.tf (root)
These outputs will be displayed after terraform apply completes.

# Output the VNet's resource ID from the Registry module
# module.vnet.resource_id refers to the output defined IN the registry module
output "vnet_id" {
  description = "The ID of the Virtual Network"
  value       = module.vnet.resource_id
}

# Output from our first local module call
# module.logging_storage.primary_blob_endpoint refers to the output
# we defined in modules/storage_account/outputs.tf
output "logging_blob_endpoint" {
  description = "Primary blob endpoint for logging storage"
  value       = module.logging_storage.primary_blob_endpoint
}

# Output from our second local module call
output "data_blob_endpoint" {
  description = "Primary blob endpoint for data storage"
  value       = module.data_storage.primary_blob_endpoint
}
How to read module outputs: The syntax is module.<MODULE_NAME>.<OUTPUT_NAME>. For example, module.logging_storage.primary_blob_endpoint means "get the primary_blob_endpoint output from the module we called logging_storage".

Step 4: Create Environment Configuration Files
Now you will create .tfvars files for different environments. This is how you manage multiple environments (dev, staging, prod) with the same Terraform code.

Why separate files?

Development environment: Use cheap "Standard" tier storage

Production environment: Use fast "Premium" tier storage

Same code, different configuration!

File 1: configs/dev.tfvars
This file contains values for the development environment:

# Development uses Standard tier (cheaper, slower)
account_tier         = "Standard"

# Storage account names - must be globally unique!
# Replace "yourinitials" with YOUR actual initials + random numbers
logging_storage_name = "yourinitialsdevlog123"
data_storage_name    = "yourinitialsdevdata123"
File 2: configs/prod.tfvars
This file contains values for the production environment:

# Production uses Premium tier (faster, more expensive)
account_tier         = "Premium"

# Different names for production accounts
logging_storage_name = "yourinitialsprodlog123"
data_storage_name    = "yourinitialsproddata123"
Important: Replace yourinitials with your actual initials and unique numbers. Storage account names must be globally unique across all of Azure, 3-24 characters, lowercase letters and numbers only.

Step 5: Initialize Terraform
Run terraform init to:

Download the Azure provider plugin

Download the Registry module (VNet)

Initialize your local modules

terraform init
